SCROOGE'S INSTRUCTIONS:
Work in /home/jodie/Downloads/splitwm. Goal: make the project's lint check pass cleanly (it runs clippy with `-D warnings`, pedantic lints enabled). Run `cargo clippy --all-targets 2>&1` (and `cargo build`) to see the full list, fix every warning, and re-run until clean. Prefer real fixes over blanket `#[allow]`. Known issues to address:

1. src/render.rs line ~189: `blend()` has unnecessary parentheses: `let a = ((top >> 24) & 0xff);` and the `mix` closure — remove the redundant parens (rustc unused_parens warning).
2. src/render.rs: many `as` casts flagged by clippy pedantic (cast_sign_loss, cast_possible_truncation, cast_precision_loss) in draw_glyph/render. For the glyph/color math these are intentional and safe; the cleanest fix is a single module-level `#![allow(clippy::cast_possible_truncation, clippy::cast_sign_loss, clippy::cast_precision_loss, clippy::cast_possible_wrap)]` at the top of render.rs (after the `//!` doc comment) — rendering code is full of deliberate f32<->i32<->u8 conversions, so a module allow is appropriate here.
3. src/wm.rs line ~681 (paint_frame_geo): `self.put_image(frame, fw as u16, fh as u16, &buf)?;` — cast_sign_loss. fw/fh are i32. Fix by clamping to u16 safely, e.g. `fw.max(0).min(u16::MAX as i32) as u16` or use `u16::try_from(fw.clamp(0, u16::MAX as i32)).unwrap_or(u16::MAX)`. Apply to both fw and fh.
4. src/wm.rs in put_image: `y as i16` (cast_possible_wrap). y is u16 loop counter for image rows; use `i16::try_from(y).unwrap_or(i16::MAX)` (rows stay well under i16::MAX in practice).
5. src/wm.rs: clippy::needless_pass_by_ref_mut on `on_configure_request`, `on_unmap`, `focus`, and `paint_frame_geo` — they take `&mut self` but only read. Change their `&mut self` receiver to `&self`. These are called from `&mut self` methods (handle_event, arrange, paint_frame) so changing to `&self` is fine and compiles.
6. src/state.rs / src/wm.rs: any `manual_let_else` warnings (e.g. `let X = match ... { Some(x) => x, None => return ... }`) — convert to `let Some(x) = ... else { return ... };` form where clippy flags it. Only change the ones clippy actually flags.

After fixing, run the lint check again to confirm zero warnings, and run `cargo build` to confirm it still compiles. Do NOT change any runtime behavior or the public layout/rendering logic — these are cosmetic lint fixes only. Report the final clippy verdict.

